38#define NS2501_VID 0x1305
39#define NS2501_DID 0x6726
40
41#define NS2501_VID_LO 0x00
42#define NS2501_VID_HI 0x01
43#define NS2501_DID_LO 0x02
44#define NS2501_DID_HI 0x03
45#define NS2501_REV 0x04
46#define NS2501_RSVD 0x05
47#define NS2501_FREQ_LO 0x06
48#define NS2501_FREQ_HI 0x07
49
50#define NS2501_REG8 0x08
51#define NS2501_8_VEN (1<<5)
52#define NS2501_8_HEN (1<<4)
53#define NS2501_8_DSEL (1<<3)
54#define NS2501_8_BPAS (1<<2)
55#define NS2501_8_RSVD (1<<1)
56#define NS2501_8_PD (1<<0)
57
58#define NS2501_REG9 0x09
59#define NS2501_9_VLOW (1<<7)
60#define NS2501_9_MSEL_MASK (0x7<<4)
61#define NS2501_9_TSEL (1<<3)
62#define NS2501_9_RSEN (1<<2)
63#define NS2501_9_RSVD (1<<1)
64#define NS2501_9_MDI (1<<0)
65
66#define NS2501_REGC 0x0c
67
68/*
69 * The following registers are not part of the official datasheet
70 * and are the result of reverse engineering.
71 */
72
73/*
74 * Register c0 controls how the DVO synchronizes with
75 * its input.
76 */
77#define NS2501_REGC0 0xc0
78#define NS2501_C0_ENABLE (1<<0) /* enable the DVO sync in general */
79#define NS2501_C0_HSYNC (1<<1) /* synchronize horizontal with input */
80#define NS2501_C0_VSYNC (1<<2) /* synchronize vertical with input */
81#define NS2501_C0_RESET (1<<7) /* reset the synchronization flip/flops */
82
83/*
84 * Register 41 is somehow related to the sync register and sync
85 * configuration. It should be 0x32 whenever regC0 is 0x05 (hsync off)
86 * and 0x00 otherwise.
87 */
88#define NS2501_REG41 0x41
89
90/*
91 * this register controls the dithering of the DVO
92 * One bit enables it, the other define the dithering depth.
93 * The higher the value, the lower the dithering depth.
94 */
95#define NS2501_F9_REG 0xf9
96#define NS2501_F9_ENABLE (1<<0) /* if set, dithering is enabled */
97#define NS2501_F9_DITHER_MASK (0x7f<<1) /* controls the dither depth */
98#define NS2501_F9_DITHER_SHIFT 1 /* shifts the dither mask */
99
100/*
101 * PLL configuration register. This is a pair of registers,
102 * one single byte register at 1B, and a pair at 1C,1D.
103 * These registers are counters/dividers.
104 */
105#define NS2501_REG1B 0x1b /* one byte PLL control register */
106#define NS2501_REG1C 0x1c /* low-part of the second register */
107#define NS2501_REG1D 0x1d /* high-part of the second register */
108
109/*
110 * Scaler control registers. Horizontal at b8,b9,
111 * vertical at 10,11. The scale factor is computed as
112 * 2^16/control-value. The low-byte comes first.
113 */
114#define NS2501_REG10 0x10 /* low-byte vertical scaler */
115#define NS2501_REG11 0x11 /* high-byte vertical scaler */
116#define NS2501_REGB8 0xb8 /* low-byte horizontal scaler */
117#define NS2501_REGB9 0xb9 /* high-byte horizontal scaler */
118
119/*
120 * Display window definition. This consists of four registers
121 * per dimension. One register pair defines the start of the
122 * display, one the end.
123 * As far as I understand, this defines the window within which
124 * the scaler samples the input.
125 */
126#define NS2501_REGC1 0xc1 /* low-byte horizontal display start */
127#define NS2501_REGC2 0xc2 /* high-byte horizontal display start */
128#define NS2501_REGC3 0xc3 /* low-byte horizontal display stop */
129#define NS2501_REGC4 0xc4 /* high-byte horizontal display stop */
130#define NS2501_REGC5 0xc5 /* low-byte vertical display start */
131#define NS2501_REGC6 0xc6 /* high-byte vertical display start */
132#define NS2501_REGC7 0xc7 /* low-byte vertical display stop */
133#define NS2501_REGC8 0xc8 /* high-byte vertical display stop */
134
135/*
136 * The following register pair seems to define the start of
137 * the vertical sync. If automatic syncing is enabled, and the
138 * register value defines a sync pulse that is later than the
139 * incoming sync, then the register value is ignored and the
140 * external hsync triggers the synchronization.
141 */
142#define NS2501_REG80 0x80 /* low-byte vsync-start */
143#define NS2501_REG81 0x81 /* high-byte vsync-start */
144
145/*
146 * The following register pair seems to define the total number
147 * of lines created at the output side of the scaler.
148 * This is again a low-high register pair.
149 */
150#define NS2501_REG82 0x82 /* output display height, low byte */
151#define NS2501_REG83 0x83 /* output display height, high byte */
152
153/*
154 * The following registers define the end of the front-porch
155 * in horizontal and vertical position and hence allow to shift
156 * the image left/right or up/down.
157 */
158#define NS2501_REG98 0x98 /* horizontal start of display + 256, low */
159#define NS2501_REG99 0x99 /* horizontal start of display + 256, high */
160#define NS2501_REG8E 0x8e /* vertical start of the display, low byte */
161#define NS2501_REG8F 0x8f /* vertical start of the display, high byte */
162
163/*
164 * The following register pair control the function of the
165 * backlight and the DVO output. To enable the corresponding
166 * function, the corresponding bit must be set in both registers.
167 */
168#define NS2501_REG34 0x34 /* DVO enable functions, first register */
169#define NS2501_REG35 0x35 /* DVO enable functions, second register */
170#define NS2501_34_ENABLE_OUTPUT (1<<0) /* enable DVO output */
171#define NS2501_34_ENABLE_BACKLIGHT (1<<1) /* enable backlight */
172
173/*
174 * Registers 9C and 9D define the vertical output offset
175 * of the visible region.
176 */
177#define NS2501_REG9C 0x9c
178#define NS2501_REG9D 0x9d
179
180/*
181 * The register 9F defines the dithering. This requires the
182 * scaler to be ON. Bit 0 enables dithering, the remaining
183 * bits control the depth of the dither. The higher the value,
184 * the LOWER the dithering amplitude. A good value seems to be
185 * 15 (total register value).
186 */
187#define NS2501_REGF9 0xf9
188#define NS2501_F9_ENABLE_DITHER (1<<0) /* enable dithering */
189#define NS2501_F9_DITHER_MASK (0x7f<<1) /* dither masking */
190#define NS2501_F9_DITHER_SHIFT 1 /* upshift of the dither mask */
191
192enum {
193 MODE_640x480,
194 MODE_800x600,
195 MODE_1024x768,
196};
197
198struct ns2501_reg {
199 uint8_t offset;
200 uint8_t value;
201};
202
203/*
204 * The following structure keeps the complete configuration of
205 * the DVO, given a specific output configuration.
206 * This is pretty much guess-work from reverse-engineering, so
207 * read all this with a grain of salt.
208 */
209struct ns2501_configuration {
210 uint8_t sync; /* configuration of the C0 register */
211 uint8_t conf; /* configuration register 8 */
212 uint8_t syncb; /* configuration register 41 */
213 uint8_t dither; /* configuration of the dithering */
214 uint8_t pll_a; /* PLL configuration, register A, 1B */
215 uint16_t pll_b; /* PLL configuration, register B, 1C/1D */
216 uint16_t hstart; /* horizontal start, registers C1/C2 */
217 uint16_t hstop; /* horizontal total, registers C3/C4 */
218 uint16_t vstart; /* vertical start, registers C5/C6 */
219 uint16_t vstop; /* vertical total, registers C7/C8 */
220 uint16_t vsync; /* manual vertical sync start, 80/81 */
221 uint16_t vtotal; /* number of lines generated, 82/83 */
222 uint16_t hpos; /* horizontal position + 256, 98/99 */
223 uint16_t vpos; /* vertical position, 8e/8f */
224 uint16_t voffs; /* vertical output offset, 9c/9d */
225 uint16_t hscale; /* horizontal scaling factor, b8/b9 */
226 uint16_t vscale; /* vertical scaling factor, 10/11 */
227};

384struct ns2501_priv {
385 bool quiet;
386 const struct ns2501_configuration *conf;
387};
388
389#define NSPTR(d) ((NS2501Ptr)(d->DriverPrivate.ptr))
390
391/*
392** Read a register from the ns2501.
393** Returns true if successful, false otherwise.
394** If it returns false, it might be wise to enable the
395** DVO with the above function.
396*/
397static bool ns2501_readb(struct intel_dvo_device *dvo, int addr, uint8_t * ch)
398{
399 struct ns2501_priv *ns = dvo->dev_priv;
400 struct i2c_adapter *adapter = dvo->i2c_bus;
401 u8 out_buf[2];
402 u8 in_buf[2];
403
404 struct i2c_msg msgs[] = {
405 {
406 .addr = dvo->slave_addr,
407 .flags = 0,
408 .len = 1,
409 .buf = out_buf,
410 },
411 {
412 .addr = dvo->slave_addr,
413 .flags = I2C_M_RD,
414 .len = 1,
415 .buf = in_buf,
416 }
417 };
418
419 out_buf[0] = addr;
420 out_buf[1] = 0;
421
422 if (i2c_transfer(adapter, msgs, 2) == 2) {
423 *ch = in_buf[0];
424 return true;
425 }
426
427 if (!ns->quiet) {
428 DRM_DEBUG_KMS
429 ("Unable to read register 0x%02x from %s:0x%02x.\n", addr,
430 adapter->name, dvo->slave_addr);
431 }
432
433 return false;
434}
435
436/*
437** Write a register to the ns2501.
438** Returns true if successful, false otherwise.
439** If it returns false, it might be wise to enable the
440** DVO with the above function.
441*/
442static bool ns2501_writeb(struct intel_dvo_device *dvo, int addr, uint8_t ch)
443{
444 struct ns2501_priv *ns = dvo->dev_priv;
445 struct i2c_adapter *adapter = dvo->i2c_bus;
446 uint8_t out_buf[2];
447
448 struct i2c_msg msg = {
449 .addr = dvo->slave_addr,
450 .flags = 0,
451 .len = 2,
452 .buf = out_buf,
453 };
454
455 out_buf[0] = addr;
456 out_buf[1] = ch;
457
458 if (i2c_transfer(adapter, &msg, 1) == 1) {
459 return true;
460 }
461
462 if (!ns->quiet) {
463 DRM_DEBUG_KMS("Unable to write register 0x%02x to %s:%d\n",
464 addr, adapter->name, dvo->slave_addr);
465 }
466
467 return false;
468}
469
470/* National Semiconductor 2501 driver for chip on i2c bus
471 * scan for the chip on the bus.
472 * Hope the VBIOS initialized the PLL correctly so we can
473 * talk to it. If not, it will not be seen and not detected.
474 * Bummer!
475 */
476static bool ns2501_init(struct intel_dvo_device *dvo,
477 struct i2c_adapter *adapter)
478{
479 /* this will detect the NS2501 chip on the specified i2c bus */
480 struct ns2501_priv *ns;
481 unsigned char ch;
482
483 ns = kzalloc(sizeof(struct ns2501_priv), GFP_KERNEL);
484 if (ns == NULL)
485 return false;
486
487 dvo->i2c_bus = adapter;
488 dvo->dev_priv = ns;
489 ns->quiet = true;
490
491 if (!ns2501_readb(dvo, NS2501_VID_LO, &ch))
492 goto out;
493
494 if (ch != (NS2501_VID & 0xff)) {
495 DRM_DEBUG_KMS("ns2501 not detected got %d: from %s Slave %d.\n",
496 ch, adapter->name, dvo->slave_addr);
497 goto out;
498 }
499
500 if (!ns2501_readb(dvo, NS2501_DID_LO, &ch))
501 goto out;
502
503 if (ch != (NS2501_DID & 0xff)) {
504 DRM_DEBUG_KMS("ns2501 not detected got %d: from %s Slave %d.\n",
505 ch, adapter->name, dvo->slave_addr);
506 goto out;
507 }
508 ns->quiet = false;
509
510 DRM_DEBUG_KMS("init ns2501 dvo controller successfully!\n");
511
512 return true;
513
514out:
515 kfree(ns);
516 return false;
517}
518
519static enum drm_connector_status ns2501_detect(struct intel_dvo_device *dvo)
520{
521 /*
522 * This is a Laptop display, it doesn't have hotplugging.
523 * Even if not, the detection bit of the 2501 is unreliable as
524 * it only works for some display types.
525 * It is even more unreliable as the PLL must be active for
526 * allowing reading from the chiop.
527 */
528 return connector_status_connected;
529}
530
531static enum drm_mode_status ns2501_mode_valid(struct intel_dvo_device *dvo,
532 struct drm_display_mode *mode)
533{
534 DRM_DEBUG_KMS
535 ("is mode valid (hdisplay=%d,htotal=%d,vdisplay=%d,vtotal=%d)\n",
536 mode->hdisplay, mode->htotal, mode->vdisplay, mode->vtotal);
537
538 /*
539 * Currently, these are all the modes I have data from.
540 * More might exist. Unclear how to find the native resolution
541 * of the panel in here so we could always accept it
542 * by disabling the scaler.
543 */
544 if ((mode->hdisplay == 640 && mode->vdisplay == 480 && mode->clock == 25175) ||
545 (mode->hdisplay == 800 && mode->vdisplay == 600 && mode->clock == 40000) ||
546 (mode->hdisplay == 1024 && mode->vdisplay == 768 && mode->clock == 65000)) {
547 return MODE_OK;
548 } else {
549 return MODE_ONE_SIZE; /* Is this a reasonable error? */
550 }
551}
552
553static void ns2501_mode_set(struct intel_dvo_device *dvo,
554 const struct drm_display_mode *mode,
555 const struct drm_display_mode *adjusted_mode)
556{
557 const struct ns2501_configuration *conf;
558 struct ns2501_priv *ns = (struct ns2501_priv *)(dvo->dev_priv);
559 int mode_idx, i;
560
561 DRM_DEBUG_KMS
562 ("set mode (hdisplay=%d,htotal=%d,vdisplay=%d,vtotal=%d).\n",
563 mode->hdisplay, mode->htotal, mode->vdisplay, mode->vtotal);
564
565 DRM_DEBUG_KMS("Detailed requested mode settings are:\n"
566 "clock : %d kHz\n"
567 "hdisplay : %d\n"
568 "hblank start : %d\n"
569 "hblank end : %d\n"
570 "hsync start : %d\n"
571 "hsync end : %d\n"
572 "htotal : %d\n"
573 "hskew : %d\n"
574 "vdisplay : %d\n"
575 "vblank start : %d\n"
576 "hblank end : %d\n"
577 "vsync start : %d\n"
578 "vsync end : %d\n"
579 "vtotal : %d\n",
580 adjusted_mode->crtc_clock,
581 adjusted_mode->crtc_hdisplay,
582 adjusted_mode->crtc_hblank_start,
583 adjusted_mode->crtc_hblank_end,
584 adjusted_mode->crtc_hsync_start,
585 adjusted_mode->crtc_hsync_end,
586 adjusted_mode->crtc_htotal,
587 adjusted_mode->crtc_hskew,
588 adjusted_mode->crtc_vdisplay,
589 adjusted_mode->crtc_vblank_start,
590 adjusted_mode->crtc_vblank_end,
591 adjusted_mode->crtc_vsync_start,
592 adjusted_mode->crtc_vsync_end,
593 adjusted_mode->crtc_vtotal);
594
595 if (mode->hdisplay == 640 && mode->vdisplay == 480)
596 mode_idx = MODE_640x480;
597 else if (mode->hdisplay == 800 && mode->vdisplay == 600)
598 mode_idx = MODE_800x600;
599 else if (mode->hdisplay == 1024 && mode->vdisplay == 768)
600 mode_idx = MODE_1024x768;
601 else
602 return;
603
604 /* Hopefully doing it every time won't hurt... */
605 for (i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(regs_init); i++)
606 ns2501_writeb(dvo, regs_init[i].offset, regs_init[i].value);
607
608 /* Write the mode-agnostic values */
609 for (i = 0; i < ARRAY_SIZE(mode_agnostic_values); i++)
610 ns2501_writeb(dvo, mode_agnostic_values[i].offset,
611 mode_agnostic_values[i].value);
612
613 /* Write now the mode-specific configuration */
614 conf = ns2501_modes + mode_idx;
615 ns->conf = conf;
616
617 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG8, conf->conf);
618 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG1B, conf->pll_a);
619 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG1C, conf->pll_b & 0xff);
620 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG1D, conf->pll_b >> 8);
621 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC1, conf->hstart & 0xff);
622 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC2, conf->hstart >> 8);
623 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC3, conf->hstop & 0xff);
624 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC4, conf->hstop >> 8);
625 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC5, conf->vstart & 0xff);
626 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC6, conf->vstart >> 8);
627 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC7, conf->vstop & 0xff);
628 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC8, conf->vstop >> 8);
629 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG80, conf->vsync & 0xff);
630 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG81, conf->vsync >> 8);
631 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG82, conf->vtotal & 0xff);
632 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG83, conf->vtotal >> 8);
633 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG98, conf->hpos & 0xff);
634 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG99, conf->hpos >> 8);
635 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG8E, conf->vpos & 0xff);
636 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG8F, conf->vpos >> 8);
637 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG9C, conf->voffs & 0xff);
638 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG9D, conf->voffs >> 8);
639 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGB8, conf->hscale & 0xff);
640 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGB9, conf->hscale >> 8);
641 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG10, conf->vscale & 0xff);
642 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG11, conf->vscale >> 8);
643 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGF9, conf->dither);
644 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG41, conf->syncb);
645 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC0, conf->sync);
646}
647
648/* set the NS2501 power state */
649static bool ns2501_get_hw_state(struct intel_dvo_device *dvo)
650{
651 unsigned char ch;
652
653 if (!ns2501_readb(dvo, NS2501_REG8, &ch))
654 return false;
655
656 return ch & NS2501_8_PD;
657}
658
659/* set the NS2501 power state */
660static void ns2501_dpms(struct intel_dvo_device *dvo, bool enable)
661{
662 struct ns2501_priv *ns = (struct ns2501_priv *)(dvo->dev_priv);
663
664 DRM_DEBUG_KMS("Trying set the dpms of the DVO to %i\n", enable);
665
666 if (enable) {
667 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC0, ns->conf->sync | 0x08);
668
669 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG41, ns->conf->syncb);
670
671 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG34, NS2501_34_ENABLE_OUTPUT);
672 msleep(15);
673
674 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG8,
675 ns->conf->conf | NS2501_8_BPAS);
676 if (!(ns->conf->conf & NS2501_8_BPAS))
677 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG8, ns->conf->conf);
678 msleep(200);
679
680 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG34,
681 NS2501_34_ENABLE_OUTPUT | NS2501_34_ENABLE_BACKLIGHT);
682
683 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REGC0, ns->conf->sync);
684 } else {
685 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG34, NS2501_34_ENABLE_OUTPUT);
686 msleep(200);
687
688 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG8, NS2501_8_VEN | NS2501_8_HEN |
689 NS2501_8_BPAS);
690 msleep(15);
691
692 ns2501_writeb(dvo, NS2501_REG34, 0x00);
693 }
694}
695
696static void ns2501_destroy(struct intel_dvo_device *dvo)
697{
698 struct ns2501_priv *ns = dvo->dev_priv;
699
700 if (ns) {
701 kfree(ns);
702 dvo->dev_priv = NULL;
703 }
704}
705
706struct intel_dvo_dev_ops ns2501_ops = {
707 .init = ns2501_init,
708 .detect = ns2501_detect,
709 .mode_valid = ns2501_mode_valid,
710 .mode_set = ns2501_mode_set,
711 .dpms = ns2501_dpms,
712 .get_hw_state = ns2501_get_hw_state,
713 .destroy = ns2501_destroy,
714};
